00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:43.820
So in a potential model, your
energy is written pairwise.

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:45.500
And so essentially
what you need to do

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:47.510
between every pair of atoms--

00:01:47.510 --> 00:01:50.547
every couple iJ--
essentially to evaluate

00:01:50.547 --> 00:01:52.130
the distance between
them and then put

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:54.270
that in some kind
of energy function.

00:01:54.270 --> 00:01:59.240
So this is clearly an
N squared operation

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:01.040
where N is the number
of atoms, since you

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.170
have to look for the
distance between every atom

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:04.610
and every other atom.

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:07.472
So if systems get
extremely big--

00:02:07.472 --> 00:02:08.930
and that's often
the reason why you

00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:11.180
want to use the pair
potentials rather than, say,

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:12.800
a quantum mechanical method--

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:14.870
N squared will get very large.

00:02:14.870 --> 00:02:17.360
And people do kind of tricks.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:19.730
If you have millions
and millions of atoms

00:02:19.730 --> 00:02:23.690
in your simulation, if you know
ahead of time that some of them

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:27.560
are very far from the atom on
which J you want to calculate--

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:28.893
energies or forces--

00:02:28.893 --> 00:02:31.060
then you really never want
to look further distance.

00:02:31.060 --> 00:02:34.280
So people do things like
keeping neighbor lists.

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.490
So literally, for every
atom you would know,

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:42.160
well, these other
items or possibly

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:45.310
in its neighbor environment.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:46.810
So then you really
only have to look

00:02:46.810 --> 00:02:49.550
for distances with those atoms.

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:51.190
So if you have a
solid, that's great.

00:02:51.190 --> 00:02:54.400
Because if you have a solid,
then the topological relation

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.070
between atoms will not change
much during the simulation.

00:02:57.070 --> 00:02:59.800
Of course, if you're simulating
a gas or a liquid, they will.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.650
And then what you have to do is
essentially update the neighbor

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:04.810
lists regularly.

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:07.510
And so there's overhead
associated with that.

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:09.760
But the benefit you get
is that you essentially

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:16.300
have an order N system rather
than an N squared system.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:21.310
I'll show you in a second
some large scale simulations.

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:25.190
Very often, you will
want to relax a system--

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:26.920
so get it to its lowest energy.

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:30.130
And very often, that's done by
calculating the forces on atoms

00:03:30.130 --> 00:03:32.545
and literally stepping
down the force.

00:03:32.545 --> 00:03:34.670
If you want to do dynamics,
Professor [? Marzari ?]

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:36.400
will later teach you
molecular dynamics.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.290
You also need the
force because the force

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:41.950
will tell you how much atoms
accelerate or decelerate.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:44.080
You will need to
calculate the force, which

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:45.340
is a potential derivative.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:46.870
So you're essentially
calculating

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:51.130
the derivative of the
total energy with respect

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:56.710
to a given position.

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:57.400
Same deal.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:00.130
That's an N squared operation.

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:02.950
You have to sum
over pairs of atoms.

00:04:02.950 --> 00:04:06.580
We have to sum over 1 all atoms
for the force on a given atom.

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:10.900
But since they're N atoms,
it's an N squared operation.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:12.760
In a lot of codes,
the minimization

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:14.710
is done by very standard
schemes-- things

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:18.519
like conjugate gradient,
Newton-Raphson, sometimes often

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:21.820
trivial line minimizations where
you literally just calculate

00:04:21.820 --> 00:04:25.990
the force and assume
some kind of elasticity

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:27.920
along the force path.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:30.640
And so if you know
the force, you

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.260
assume you know what
the curvature is

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:33.593
of the energy in that direction.

00:04:33.593 --> 00:04:35.830
You kind of can make an
approximation to its minimum

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:39.520
when you do that iteratively.

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:47.560
So you can do that with
very large simulations.

