00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:39.980
Another very practical issue
that I'm sure a lot of you

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:42.680
are familiar with.

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:44.660
Even when you have
a billion atoms,

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:46.320
it's actually still very small.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.710
I actually think if you do the
calculation, a million atoms

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:53.030
is, for a lot of materials,
a cube of just about 200

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:56.120
Angstrom on the side
so you're still,

00:07:56.120 --> 00:07:59.840
if these were finite systems,
would be very small systems.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:01.310
So to get rid of
boundary effects,

00:08:01.310 --> 00:08:03.518
you almost always use what's
called periodic boundary

00:08:03.518 --> 00:08:07.550
conditions in simulations in
as many directions as you can.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:09.950
And of course, what a
periodic boundary condition

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:16.290
means is that if you have some
unit, if you have some unit,

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:18.080
you essentially
repeat it next to it.

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:21.250
So this end here is
the same as that end,

00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:24.120
and this end here is
the same as that end.

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.220
So people always
ask you how many

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:28.140
atoms do you have
in your simulation,

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.810
and the answer is infinite.

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:33.960
It's just that you only have
a finite number of degrees

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:38.669
of freedom because it's
these atoms here do

00:08:38.669 --> 00:08:41.460
exactly the same as these here.

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:43.299
But the answer is infinite.

00:08:43.299 --> 00:08:45.690
So we don't really work
with small systems.

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:46.530
Or, rarely.

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:50.260
I mean, sometimes we
work with finite systems.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:52.470
So what's the
repeat unit you use?

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:54.990
Well, if you're studying
a periodic material,

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:56.177
then it's easy.

00:08:56.177 --> 00:08:58.260
If you study, say, a perfect
crystalline material,

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:01.710
here's a perovskite unit,
so that's what you repeat.

00:09:01.710 --> 00:09:05.165
Because the material already
has periodicity implied in it.

00:09:05.165 --> 00:09:06.540
So at that point,
you're actually

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:09.240
not making any approximation.

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.820
You're not forcing
anything on the material--

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.850
not when you do a static
calculation that it already

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:16.165
doesn't have.

00:09:16.165 --> 00:09:17.790
Of course, when you
do dynamics, you're

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:19.207
enforcing something
because you're

00:09:19.207 --> 00:09:24.330
saying that in dynamics, the
translational symmetry is

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:27.810
temporarily broken because this
atom can vibrate independent

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:29.190
of that one.

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:32.370
And so, then, when you
improve impulse periodicity,

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:35.440
you are imposing that
these vibrate together.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.430
So in some sense,
you're imposing a cutoff

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:40.560
on the frequencies of
vibrations that can occur.

00:09:43.490 --> 00:09:46.490
If systems don't
have periodicity,

00:09:46.490 --> 00:09:48.410
you typically tend
to enforce it.

00:09:48.410 --> 00:09:52.250
If I took this perovskite
and I made one defect--

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:55.070
say I wanted to study
oxygen vacancy so I take out

00:09:55.070 --> 00:09:59.570
the oxygen vacancy, I lose all
translational periodicity now.

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:02.420
But what you do is you
tend to impose it back

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:03.560
by repeating the defect.

00:10:08.410 --> 00:10:10.610
It's going to be slow.

00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:16.150
So let's say I've taken
out an oxygen here.

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:19.600
I repeat the defect
so that, in essence,

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:21.130
I just have a bigger unit cell.

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:22.810
But it's one with
a defect in it.

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:25.000
This is now my unit cell.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.910
And that's called a
supercell approximation.

00:10:28.910 --> 00:10:32.410
So you make a cell that's
big enough so that you

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:34.700
hope that these defects--

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:35.950
I don't know how you call it--

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:42.190
don't interact because
then, if you have N cells,

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:45.910
your calculation just has
the energy of N defects.

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:46.480
OK?

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:48.490
And the critical
assumption is, of course,

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:49.918
that they don't interact.

00:10:49.918 --> 00:10:51.460
Because if they
interact, then you're

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:53.020
not modeling an isolated defect.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:56.900
You're modeling a defect that's
interacting with other ones.

00:10:56.900 --> 00:10:59.920
So how do they
interact typically?

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:01.315
It's kind of important to know.

00:11:01.315 --> 00:11:03.940
This is one of these things that
you're going to do in the lab.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:06.600
You should always check
conversions if you can.

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:08.350
The problem is that
often you already work

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:10.900
at your computational limits
for size of supercells,

00:11:10.900 --> 00:11:13.072
so it's easier said than done.

00:11:13.072 --> 00:11:14.530
In an ideal world,
you say, well, I

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:18.400
calculate bigger and bigger, and
if the answer doesn't change,

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:19.270
I take it.

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:22.095
But usually, you work so much
at your computational edge

00:11:22.095 --> 00:11:24.220
already that you can't make
them bigger and bigger.

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:26.220
A lot of people forget
that [? to ?] [? check ?]

00:11:26.220 --> 00:11:28.720
[? conversions, ?] you
also can make it smaller.

00:11:28.720 --> 00:11:30.160
And if it doesn't
change much, you

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:32.740
were probably already converged.

00:11:32.740 --> 00:11:36.190
But it's useful to know
how these things usually

00:11:36.190 --> 00:11:37.340
interact with each other.

00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:40.780
So that gives you some sense
of how far you have to go.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:43.300
There's often the direct
sort of interaction.

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:44.890
If you work with
a pair potential,

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:48.320
then you can actually see the
range of the pair potential.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:50.170
That's usually not the problem.

00:11:50.170 --> 00:11:53.200
Rarely do you have potentials
that are relevant, large,

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.720
and over large distances
that you need to make

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:57.700
really large supercells.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.755
But there can be other
energetic effects.

00:11:59.755 --> 00:12:02.432
If you have electrostatics
in your system,

00:12:02.432 --> 00:12:04.390
that will give you very
long range interaction.

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:05.860
If that's a charge defect--

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:08.350
which it is in a perovskite--

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:10.150
you will have a very strong one.

00:12:10.150 --> 00:12:14.200
Actually, if we truly
did a charge defect

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:15.910
in that supercell,
what would happen?

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:23.240
If that supercell
became charged--

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:25.070
so let's say I
took out an oxygen

00:12:25.070 --> 00:12:27.350
2 minus, which means
the supercell now

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:29.180
has a net positive charge--

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:34.140
what would happen?

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:37.790
You'd have an infinite energy
because you would essentially

00:12:37.790 --> 00:12:43.460
have a positive charge
interacting with only other net

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:45.260
positive charges.

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:47.840
And at any distance, if
you do an infinite system,

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:50.763
that gives you an
infinite energy.

00:12:50.763 --> 00:12:52.180
So that's something
that you would

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:54.450
have to explicitly take out.

00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:58.150
Now you say, well,
I'll compensate

00:12:58.150 --> 00:13:03.290
with a negative charge because
that's what happens in reality.

00:13:03.290 --> 00:13:05.683
If I take out an oxygen,
those two electrons

00:13:05.683 --> 00:13:07.600
of that or O2 minus are
going to go somewhere,

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:10.040
so it's going to create
a net positive charge.

00:13:10.040 --> 00:13:12.990
So then you have a dipole.

00:13:12.990 --> 00:13:15.750
So let's say I have
sort of plus, minus,

00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:18.060
and I have a dipole now.

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:20.160
So now I have
dipoles interacting.

00:13:24.690 --> 00:13:26.880
Dipoles will not give
you infinite energy,

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:31.120
but they will give you a
fairly long range energy tail.

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:33.160
And if you're smart about it--

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:36.360
so the brute force way to
convert supercell calculation

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:39.840
is always to push him as
hard as you can and hope

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:42.545
and sort of see the energy
converge of the defect.

00:13:42.545 --> 00:13:43.920
But if you're
smart about it, you

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:46.050
can often do much
smaller cell calculations

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:48.900
and explicitly take
out the term that's

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:51.990
the defect-defect interaction.

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:54.720
Which is, if you know
that this is a dipole,

00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:59.340
you know what the form is of
it, and you can take it out.

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:02.940
Other things that often
cause havoc is relaxation.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:05.460
If I were to put
a really big ion

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:08.580
in the center of that
perovskite unit cell,

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:12.030
I would build up a strain
field and the different defects

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:15.060
would interact through
their strain field.

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:16.980
So, rarely do you
actually interact

00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:19.180
through the direct energetics.

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:23.460
You often interact
through secondary effects.

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:27.960
Another way they often interact
which is very indirect.

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:29.970
If you put in your
defect and you

00:14:29.970 --> 00:14:36.140
relax the volume
of the supercell,

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:38.720
then that will interfere
with the relaxation

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:41.340
of the supercell next to it.

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.570
So you get a strain field
just through the homogeneous.

00:14:44.570 --> 00:14:46.430
You get an extra
energy term just

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:48.393
through the homogeneous
strain interaction.

00:14:48.393 --> 00:14:50.060
So these are all
things to consider when

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:52.720
you do supercell calculations.

00:14:55.910 --> 00:14:59.030
We're trying something new
where we save the annotations

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:02.270
we make on the slides, but
it seems to be really slow.

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:06.770
So I may not be able
to keep that up.

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:11.720
OK, so this I went over--
the kind of convergence.

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:14.540
You know, here's
a typical example.

00:15:14.540 --> 00:15:16.400
I don't know if this is typical.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:18.592
This is the vacancy
formation energy in aluminum.

00:15:18.592 --> 00:15:20.300
Now, this is done with
quantum mechanics,

00:15:20.300 --> 00:15:22.730
versus the number of
atoms in the supercell.

00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:26.450
And you know, this
is one of these

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:30.402
that you really don't
know if you're converged.

00:15:30.402 --> 00:15:32.360
I mean, it depends on
how accurate you want it.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:36.710
If you really only care that
it's between 0.7 and 0.75,

00:15:36.710 --> 00:15:38.100
you're probably OK.

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:40.410
But if you did this
point and that point,

00:15:40.410 --> 00:15:42.387
you'd probably think
you're converged.

00:15:42.387 --> 00:15:43.970
But then, if you
look at the next one,

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:46.012
you're actually going back
up a little bit again.

00:15:46.012 --> 00:15:48.980
So it's sometimes very hard
to figure out whether you're

00:15:48.980 --> 00:15:50.314
actually converged.

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:55.955
OK.

00:15:55.955 --> 00:15:58.080
So that was a few practical
issues to sort of start

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:00.163
gearing you up for the lab.

00:16:00.163 --> 00:16:01.830
What I want to do now
is talk explicitly

00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:04.620
about some of the formal
failures of pair potentials

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:06.250
and go on to correct them.

00:16:06.250 --> 00:16:08.490
And the first one is the
vacancy formation energy

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:13.500
which is, if you look at
historically when people

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:19.470
started doing simulations late
1950s, 1960s, into the '70s,

00:16:19.470 --> 00:16:22.170
people thought that
whenever there was something

00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:24.720
wrong with the outcome that
they just needed better

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:27.810
parameters in the potential.

00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:31.992
And it's actually rather
recent-- sort of 1980s--

00:16:31.992 --> 00:16:34.200
that people figured out that
there were really formal

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:37.110
problems and that there were
certain things you could not

00:16:37.110 --> 00:16:38.760
get right-- never--

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:41.130
with a potential because
the problem of the form

00:16:41.130 --> 00:16:42.780
rather than of the parameters.

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:45.630
And a critical
number in that work

00:16:45.630 --> 00:16:47.940
was actually the vacancy
formation energy which

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.530
nobody could ever get right.

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:50.940
And I'll show in a second why.

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:55.110
Here's an FCC crystal.

00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:59.280
So let's calculate the pair
approximation to the vacancy

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:01.080
formation energy.

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:03.720
What do I do when
I make a vacancy?

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:08.579
What I do is that I
take this central atom

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:12.339
and I move it somewhere
else in the bulk.

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:16.020
So in some sense, I make
my system one side bigger.

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:19.300
So let's calculate the
energy balance of that.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.390
So the vacancy formation energy.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:25.020
OK.

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:26.339
What do I destroy?

00:17:26.339 --> 00:17:31.440
I destroy 12 bonds because this
atom is coordinated 12-fold

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:32.790
in FCC.

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:34.140
So I destroy 12 bonds.

00:17:36.790 --> 00:17:41.310
I lose 12 times the bond energy.

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:44.270
But then, of course, I put it
back somewhere in the bulk.

00:17:44.270 --> 00:17:49.660
And so I gained the
cohesive energy of one atom.

00:17:49.660 --> 00:17:50.590
OK?

00:17:50.590 --> 00:17:54.130
And what's the cohesive
energy per atom in FCC?

00:17:54.130 --> 00:17:57.310
It's 6 times the bond
energy because there

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:59.740
are 12 bonds around an
atom, but every bond

00:17:59.740 --> 00:18:01.430
is shared between two.

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:01.930
OK?

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:04.240
So there's six per atom.

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:07.870
So the vacancy formation
is really minus 12 times

00:18:07.870 --> 00:18:10.960
the bond energy plus 6
times the bond energy.

00:18:13.990 --> 00:18:19.890
So what it is is minus 6
times the bond the energy.

00:18:19.890 --> 00:18:25.260
So essentially, it's
minus the cohesive energy.

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:29.120
The cohesive energy per atom.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:31.100
And that's essentially
what you will always

00:18:31.100 --> 00:18:33.270
find repair potentials.

00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:35.690
Now, I did a static
approximation.

00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:37.100
I assumed that
all of these bonds

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:39.770
were kind of unchanged
as I took the atom out.

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:42.500
In reality, if I take
that central atom out,

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:44.570
the atoms around it
will relax somewhat

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:46.760
and change their bond energy.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:49.190
But you'll see this when
you do this in the lab.

00:18:49.190 --> 00:18:52.550
That will make it from one
time the cohesive energy

00:18:52.550 --> 00:18:56.330
to something like 0.9 or 0.95
times the cohesive energy.

00:18:56.330 --> 00:18:58.340
Essentially, you find
in pair potentials

00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:00.350
that the vacancy
formation energy

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:03.090
is about the cohesive energy.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:06.450
If you look, on the other
hand, at experimental results

00:19:06.450 --> 00:19:07.550
for the cohesive energy--

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:17.130
[INAUDIBLE]---- here's
some experimental data.

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:20.240
So this is for FCC metals,
and this is for Leonard-Jones,

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:21.230
and for noble gases.

00:19:21.230 --> 00:19:24.590
The ratio of the
vacancy formation energy

00:19:24.590 --> 00:19:27.170
to the cohesive energy.

00:19:27.170 --> 00:19:31.590
And what you see is that,
in the noble gases--

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:33.710
which you think of as
well-described by pair

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:35.000
potentials--

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.550
you're reasonably close.

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:39.410
Because remember,
noble gases are just

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:42.230
inert shells interacting through
Van der Waals interaction,

00:19:42.230 --> 00:19:45.470
and that's how we came up with
the Leonard-Jones potential.

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:49.760
But if you look at the metals,
the vacancy formation energy

00:19:49.760 --> 00:19:52.220
is actually only
a small fraction

00:19:52.220 --> 00:19:55.370
of the cohesive energy.

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:58.220
And we can never get that
low with pair potentials.

00:19:58.220 --> 00:19:59.330
Never.

00:19:59.330 --> 00:19:59.900
OK?

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:04.100
Unless you maybe really
have the most odd form

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:06.530
of a pair potential.

00:20:06.530 --> 00:20:09.470
But the reason is because there
are certain physics missing

00:20:09.470 --> 00:20:11.052
from pair potentials.

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:28.220
So actually, let me go back
for a second to the pair

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:30.380
potentials.

00:20:30.380 --> 00:20:34.850
What's the physics here of why
the vacancy formation energy is

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:39.440
so low in real materials?

00:20:39.440 --> 00:20:43.070
Remember what I said
before, that bonding

00:20:43.070 --> 00:20:47.330
in metals, the bonding
energy goes not linear

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:49.100
in the coordination number.

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:51.560
It's more something like
a rough approximation

00:20:51.560 --> 00:20:54.980
would be the square root
of the coordination number.

00:20:54.980 --> 00:20:59.020
But essentially, when
you go from 1 to 2 bonds,

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:00.770
your energy goes down
a lot more than when

00:21:00.770 --> 00:21:04.250
you go from 11 to 12 bonds.

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:07.850
So why is the vacancy
formation energy so low?

00:21:07.850 --> 00:21:10.100
Well, if you think about
what you do when you take out

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:14.990
an atom, you make a lot
of the atoms around it

00:21:14.990 --> 00:21:19.260
go from 12 coordination to 11.

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:27.498
So they lose a lot less than
1/12 of the cohesive energy

00:21:27.498 --> 00:21:29.290
because the cohesive
energy you could think

00:21:29.290 --> 00:21:32.830
of as the average of all bonds.

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:36.430
But around the vacancy, you are
just reducing the coordination

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:37.840
from 12 to 11.

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:41.230
You can actually
make a simple model

00:21:41.230 --> 00:21:47.680
if you said that the
cohesive energy was

00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:54.800
some constant times the square
root of the coordination.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:57.020
So rather than linear in
the coordination, which

00:21:57.020 --> 00:22:01.370
is what we would get in pair
of potentials, if you calculate

00:22:01.370 --> 00:22:03.800
the vacancy formation
energy in this model--

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:10.410
let's do it for FCC.

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:11.820
In FCC, Z is 12.

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:20.840
The vacancy formation
energy, what would it be?

00:22:20.840 --> 00:22:25.480
Well, if we put the
atom somewhere back in,

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:31.070
we would gain Z times
the square root of 12.

00:22:31.070 --> 00:22:34.820
And then, as we take it
out, what do we lose?

00:22:34.820 --> 00:22:41.540
For 12 atoms, we go from
coordination 12 to 11.

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:46.250
So this is the atom in the bulk.

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:53.010
This is actually the change
around where we made the hole.

00:22:58.430 --> 00:23:01.900
And if you actually
calculate that--

00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:04.690
the vacancy formation energy
over the cohesive energy--

00:23:09.380 --> 00:23:15.530
you find that that's 1 plus
12 times square root of 11

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:18.590
over square root of 12 minus 1.

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:21.680
And it's about 0.49.

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:23.330
So in a square
root model, you're

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:25.970
already much closer
to the experiment

00:23:25.970 --> 00:23:29.540
where the vacancy
formation energy

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:32.660
is a much smaller fraction
of the cohesive energy.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:44.890
Another critical
piece of information

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:47.890
was surface relaxation,
which people

00:23:47.890 --> 00:23:52.270
had been seeing with
[? LEEDs. ?] If you look

00:23:52.270 --> 00:23:55.960
at a metal, typically
if you create a surface,

00:23:55.960 --> 00:23:59.830
the difference between the
first and the second layer

00:23:59.830 --> 00:24:01.790
becomes smaller.

00:24:01.790 --> 00:24:05.360
So in a metal, the first
layer tends to relax inward.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:11.973
And can somebody explain
to me why that happens?

00:24:11.973 --> 00:24:13.390
And typically, you
don't see this.

00:24:13.390 --> 00:24:16.330
In pair potentials,
you very often

00:24:16.330 --> 00:24:18.200
have about the same distance.

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:20.530
So the first to second
neighbor distance

00:24:20.530 --> 00:24:25.090
is often bulk-like and in some
cases actually relaxes outwards

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:27.010
because of competing forces.

00:24:27.010 --> 00:24:32.820
But in almost all real systems,
it tends to relax inward.

00:24:32.820 --> 00:24:35.360
Why do you think that is?

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:36.500
Yes, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.106
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:44.893 --> 00:24:45.560
PROFESSOR: True.

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:49.180
But I'm not sure
that that necessarily

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:52.570
makes it relax inward.

00:24:52.570 --> 00:24:54.820
The reason it relaxes
inward is because the bonds

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:57.228
between the first and the
second layer strengthen.

00:24:57.228 --> 00:24:58.770
That's really what
is a sign of them.

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:00.960
And why do they strengthen?

00:25:00.960 --> 00:25:03.630
Because the surface
is under-coordinated.

00:25:03.630 --> 00:25:06.090
Remember, if you go
to lower coordination,

00:25:06.090 --> 00:25:07.560
you're effectively--

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:09.270
although you're losing
energy and that's

00:25:09.270 --> 00:25:10.740
why there's surface energy--

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:15.300
but the energy per bond is
actually becoming stronger.

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:17.850
Remember that I showed you
the potentials for copper?

00:25:17.850 --> 00:25:25.090
Remember that for the
copper II molecule--

00:25:25.090 --> 00:25:29.410
so where you just had one bond--
had the strongest potential.

00:25:29.410 --> 00:25:31.170
The equation of
state gave you where

00:25:31.170 --> 00:25:34.270
your were 12-fold coordinate
gave you much weaker potential.

00:25:34.270 --> 00:25:37.080
So you see that in
surfaces as well.

00:25:37.080 --> 00:25:41.700
If you cut away the bonds here,
the remaining ones strengthen

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:43.110
and they pull the layer in.

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:51.890
The other problem that's
common in pair potential

00:25:51.890 --> 00:25:53.473
which I won't say
much about is what's

00:25:53.473 --> 00:25:55.040
called the Cauchy problem.

00:25:55.040 --> 00:26:01.430
If you write down the
relation between the stress

00:26:01.430 --> 00:26:03.950
and the strain
tensor and so this

00:26:03.950 --> 00:26:05.810
is the matrix of
elastic constant that

00:26:05.810 --> 00:26:11.130
for pair potential C12 and
C44 are always the same.

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:13.400
And this has something to
do with there actually being

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:15.170
a zero-energy strain mold.

00:26:15.170 --> 00:26:16.880
Remember that I showed you this?

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:19.460
It's related to the same
issue that in a cubic

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:23.330
or in a square model, you
can actually kind of slide it

00:26:23.330 --> 00:26:25.370
without any energy change.

00:26:25.370 --> 00:26:27.410
And that actually
puts a constraint

00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:29.450
on the elastic constant,
which essentially

00:26:29.450 --> 00:26:33.110
translates to C12 being C44.

00:26:36.230 --> 00:26:38.930
And the last one--

00:26:38.930 --> 00:26:40.880
if you're a practicing
material scientist--

00:26:40.880 --> 00:26:43.730
may be one of the
important ones.

00:26:43.730 --> 00:26:47.270
But you can essentially not
predict crystal structure

00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:50.900
in anything that's covalent.

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:52.880
And metals are covalent.

00:26:52.880 --> 00:26:55.160
I know they teach you there's
metallic, covalent, then

00:26:55.160 --> 00:26:56.030
ionic bonding.

00:26:56.030 --> 00:27:00.450
But metallic is just
delocalized covalent.

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:02.188
And the reason is--

00:27:02.188 --> 00:27:03.980
I think you can already
see-- first of all,

00:27:03.980 --> 00:27:07.160
potentials tend to go
to close packing always

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:10.880
because they just they want to
have as many atoms around them

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:12.680
as possible because
that's how you

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:14.240
bring the cohesive energy down.

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:17.540
And they don't count that
cost, that if you bring more

00:27:17.540 --> 00:27:21.290
around you, your bound
strength weakens.

00:27:21.290 --> 00:27:23.550
And they have no
directional dependence,

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:27.860
so they miss those two
important components

00:27:27.860 --> 00:27:29.378
to get crystal structure right.

00:27:29.378 --> 00:27:31.170
You can actually do
some theory about this,

00:27:31.170 --> 00:27:32.720
which was done
already in the '70s

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:36.020
that you actually
need what's called

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:39.620
at least the fourth moment
of the density of states

00:27:39.620 --> 00:27:41.030
to get crystal structure right.

00:27:41.030 --> 00:27:44.100
And that turns out to be at
least a four-body effect.

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:47.970
So if you actually thought of
potentials as an expansion--

00:27:47.970 --> 00:27:52.020
so I'm going to write the energy
as a constant plus an expansion

00:27:52.020 --> 00:27:54.570
in two-body terms, three-body
terms, four-body terms, et

00:27:54.570 --> 00:27:56.900
cetera, which we don't
even know would converge--

00:27:56.900 --> 00:27:59.840
you would have to go at
least up to the fourth order

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:02.360
to get crystal structure
differences right.

00:28:06.180 --> 00:28:09.270
OK, so how do you
fix the problem?

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:11.610
There are essentially,
if you look

00:28:11.610 --> 00:28:18.630
at the literature of empirical
models, two avenues to go.

00:28:18.630 --> 00:28:23.850
You can either make what's
called cluster potentials.

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:26.760
And so, if you don't like
a two-body potential,

00:28:26.760 --> 00:28:28.482
you can make a
three-body potential.

00:28:28.482 --> 00:28:29.940
And the advantage
of that, once you

00:28:29.940 --> 00:28:35.850
have a three-body potential,
you can see angular dependence.

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:41.490
Because if I have three
atoms and they don't interact

00:28:41.490 --> 00:28:44.400
just pairwise, but there's
a [? two ?] three-body,

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:48.330
I can include this
bonding angle.

00:28:48.330 --> 00:28:52.560
A bonding angle is truly
a three-body concept.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:56.040
So you can start building
an angular dependence.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:29:01.590
The other direction to go
is go to pair functionals.

00:29:01.590 --> 00:29:05.160
So you still want to write
the [? energies ?] pairwise--

00:29:05.160 --> 00:29:06.970
some pairwise summation.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:09.100
You just don't want the
cohesive energy per atom

00:29:09.100 --> 00:29:12.510
to go linear with
what you sum pairwise

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:16.980
or what you sum as its
environment pairwise.

00:29:16.980 --> 00:29:19.020
So we're going to deal
with both in class.

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:22.236
Today, I'm going to mainly
do pair functionals.

00:29:22.236 --> 00:29:27.240
Pair functionals tends to be
most applicable to metals.

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:29.790
Where I would say the
square root depends,

00:29:29.790 --> 00:29:33.570
that effect is strongest,
whereas cluster potentials

00:29:33.570 --> 00:29:35.490
or many body
potentials in general

00:29:35.490 --> 00:29:39.270
tend to be more favored in
the organic literature--

00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:42.510
both organic chemistry
and polymer chemistry.

00:29:42.510 --> 00:29:44.970
And so, going to that.

00:29:54.060 --> 00:29:56.730
So there's a whole
class of methods

00:29:56.730 --> 00:29:59.108
which are called
effective medium theories.

00:29:59.108 --> 00:30:00.900
The version of it that
I'm going to discuss

00:30:00.900 --> 00:30:03.400
is what's called the embedded
atom method, which is probably

00:30:03.400 --> 00:30:06.510
the most popular one.

00:30:06.510 --> 00:30:09.150
This was developed by [? Mike ?]
[? Baskis ?] [? and ?]

00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:14.460
[? Murray ?] [? Dahl ?] I
think going back to the '80s.

00:30:14.460 --> 00:30:16.630
Mid '80s, or
something like that.

00:30:16.630 --> 00:30:19.500
And it's probably
now the most popular

00:30:19.500 --> 00:30:21.780
of the sort of empirical
energy schemes.

00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:23.340
If you look back
at those papers,

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:27.090
those papers have now
over 1,000 citations.

00:30:27.090 --> 00:30:29.265
And the idea is
extremely simple.

00:30:29.265 --> 00:30:31.590
It's, if you understand
the source of the problem--

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:33.120
that our energy
should not be linear

00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:35.483
with coordination-- that's
what you're going to fix.

00:30:35.483 --> 00:30:36.900
So in these models,
what you do is

00:30:36.900 --> 00:30:41.460
you write the energy per atom
as a function of the number

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:43.200
of bonds around it.

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:46.650
It's just that F
should not be linear.

00:30:46.650 --> 00:30:50.850
And so that's why they call it
energy functionals rather than

00:30:50.850 --> 00:30:52.650
a pair potential.

00:30:52.650 --> 00:30:56.832
The question is, how do you
measure number of bonds?

00:30:56.832 --> 00:30:59.040
And if you sort think about
it, if you think yourself

00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:01.635
back in the '80s,
how do you want

00:31:01.635 --> 00:31:03.570
to measure number of bonds?

00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:06.900
You don't really want
to do it discreetly.

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:08.970
Because you could
say, well, maybe I'm

00:31:08.970 --> 00:31:12.780
just going to count atoms
within a two-Angstrom radius,

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:14.100
or some radius.

00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:16.590
The problem is, as soon as
you measure it discretely,

00:31:16.590 --> 00:31:19.620
you're going to have to
deal with discontinuities.

00:31:19.620 --> 00:31:21.630
As atoms move in and
out of that radius,

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:26.070
suddenly you've got 14 things
around you instead of 15.

00:31:26.070 --> 00:31:29.310
So you would always
have super large forces

00:31:29.310 --> 00:31:32.100
because of those discontinuities
around your [? cutoff ?]

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:32.800
interface.

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:37.860
So what you need is a smooth
count of coordination.

00:31:37.860 --> 00:31:42.150
And the one they came up with
in the embedded atom method

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:44.670
is literally, you
measure the electron

00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:49.110
density being projected on
you from your neighbors.

00:31:49.110 --> 00:31:50.070
It's ironic.

00:31:50.070 --> 00:31:52.590
I'll show you later the
formal justification

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:55.050
for the embedded atom
method which has a lot more

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:57.210
to do with quantum mechanics.

00:31:57.210 --> 00:32:01.000
But that was actually a
justification after the fact.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.080
The original idea
came up with sort of,

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:06.450
you really want to have a
continuous measure of bumbling

00:32:06.450 --> 00:32:07.420
around you.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:11.280
And so the idea is that you're
going to do something like,

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:13.530
I have a central atom.

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:17.250
I have other atoms around me.

00:32:17.250 --> 00:32:20.520
How do I measure how much these
contribute to my neighborhood?

00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:24.840
Well, these have some electron
density functions around them.

00:32:24.840 --> 00:32:30.770
Their atomic electron
density I'm sort of drawing.

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:33.320
And they all project
onto that central atom.

00:32:33.320 --> 00:32:36.650
You count up how much
electron density there

00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:40.162
and that's somehow a measurement
of your neighborhood.

00:32:40.162 --> 00:32:41.870
And you see, that's
going to roughly have

00:32:41.870 --> 00:32:42.662
the right behavior.

00:32:42.662 --> 00:32:43.760
It's continuous.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:47.270
As atoms move farther away,
they still contribute,

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:48.650
but they contribute less.

00:32:48.650 --> 00:32:50.090
So it is a continuous measure.

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:53.780
And the more
density you project,

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:57.840
either the closer by the
atoms are or the more of them

00:32:57.840 --> 00:32:58.340
there are.

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:05.960
OK.

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:07.820
So this is the idea of
the electron density.

00:33:07.820 --> 00:33:10.430
You're going to actually
calculate the electron density

00:33:10.430 --> 00:33:14.060
on a site as a measurement in
some sense of the coordination

00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:18.080
as a sum of electron densities
coming from its neighboring

00:33:18.080 --> 00:33:19.890
atoms, J. OK?

00:33:23.230 --> 00:33:28.600
What electron densities you
use is kind of less relevant.

00:33:28.600 --> 00:33:31.330
In the original embedded atom
and in most embedded atom codes

00:33:31.330 --> 00:33:34.930
still, they use essentially
the atomic densities.

00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:38.950
So people have calculated
the atomic electron densities

00:33:38.950 --> 00:33:40.180
with [INAUDIBLE] methods.

00:33:40.180 --> 00:33:42.700
And they're actually tabulated
in these Clementi and Roetti

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:43.200
tables.

00:33:46.520 --> 00:33:48.270
And you know, I'm just
sort of showing you

00:33:48.270 --> 00:33:50.480
that they're basically
parameterized

00:33:50.480 --> 00:33:53.960
by a bunch of Gaussians,
but you can get those.

00:33:53.960 --> 00:33:56.970
So you can get those functions.

00:33:56.970 --> 00:33:58.040
We skipped through that.

00:33:58.040 --> 00:33:59.070
OK.

00:33:59.070 --> 00:34:01.590
So remember that if you have--

00:34:01.590 --> 00:34:02.615
yes, sir.

00:34:02.615 --> 00:34:05.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:06.970
PROFESSOR: Correct.

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:09.100
Correct.

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:11.110
Well, it's a distance
dependent function.

00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:13.670
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:13.670 --> 00:34:14.510
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:34:14.510 --> 00:34:14.929
Yeah.

00:34:14.929 --> 00:34:16.929
So it's sort of what
people in quantum mechanics

00:34:16.929 --> 00:34:19.159
think of as sort of non
self-consistent methods.

00:34:22.772 --> 00:34:25.400
You literally treat
the electron density

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:29.150
of the crystal as the overlap
of the atomic densities

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:31.400
of the atoms.

00:34:31.400 --> 00:34:33.650
The reason that saves you
here is that you're actually

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:36.043
not going to do quantum
mechanics on that density,

00:34:36.043 --> 00:34:37.460
and you're just
using that density

00:34:37.460 --> 00:34:40.260
as some measure of coordination.

00:34:40.260 --> 00:34:44.924
So [INAUDIBLE] I
skipped some slides.

00:34:51.322 --> 00:34:52.739
Somehow, I lost
the slide in here.

00:34:52.739 --> 00:34:53.449
Sorry about that.

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:00.300
OK.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:00.883
You know what?

00:35:00.883 --> 00:35:02.163
I put it in the wrong place.

00:35:02.163 --> 00:35:03.070
Here we go.

00:35:03.070 --> 00:35:08.940
So the way you write the energy
in the embedded atom method

00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:12.360
is you write it as the
embedding energy, which

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:15.780
is you sum over every atom.

00:35:15.780 --> 00:35:19.890
And you're looking for
it's cohesive energy, which

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:25.680
is some function F
of the neighborhood

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:27.750
measurements, which
is the electron

00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:29.280
density at the site of i.

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:32.190
And that's your summing
from these functions F

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:33.600
which are the
projected densities

00:35:33.600 --> 00:35:38.580
from all the other atoms J.

00:35:38.580 --> 00:35:43.440
So this is the nonlinear
part of the energy.

00:35:43.440 --> 00:35:49.350
Typically, that is supplemented
with a pair potential.

00:35:49.350 --> 00:35:51.840
So the standard
embedded atom method

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:53.760
is a pair potential
which is often

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:57.930
just used for having a
repulsive part and a nonlinear

00:35:57.930 --> 00:35:59.920
embedding energy.

00:35:59.920 --> 00:36:02.880
So that means we have
to solve three problems,

00:36:02.880 --> 00:36:04.230
really-- the one we've solved.

00:36:04.230 --> 00:36:06.420
You need to know what the
electron densities are.

00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:08.170
Take the Clementi
and Roetti tables.

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:10.170
You need to know what the
embedding function is,

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:12.690
and you need to know what
the pair potential is.

00:36:12.690 --> 00:36:14.240
The pair potential,
to be honest,

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:15.850
you can use almost anything.

00:36:15.850 --> 00:36:19.440
It's mainly used for the
hardcore repulsion part.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:21.900
You don't want the atoms
to fly into each other.

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:26.700
Typically, they use some
screened electrostatic form

00:36:26.700 --> 00:36:30.990
which is essentially the
product of charge distribution

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:32.740
functions on atoms.

00:36:32.740 --> 00:36:35.820
But you know, nothing would
stop you if you really wanted to

00:36:35.820 --> 00:36:37.350
from using a Leonard-Jones.

00:36:37.350 --> 00:36:39.000
I'll show you in a
second that there

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:44.010
is ambiguity about the division
of energy between the embedding

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:47.305
part and the pair
potential is not unique.

00:36:47.305 --> 00:36:49.680
So that means, every time you
change your pair potential,

00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:51.597
you'll have to change
your embedding function.

00:36:51.597 --> 00:36:53.933
I'll show that in a second.

00:36:53.933 --> 00:36:55.725
What do you use for
the embedding function?

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:04.620
There are two ways
that it can be done.

00:37:04.620 --> 00:37:08.750
People have written
down analytical forms

00:37:08.750 --> 00:37:10.760
with some theoretical
justification

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:12.890
that I'm not going to go into.

00:37:12.890 --> 00:37:14.960
There's actually an
excellent review article

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:16.490
on the embedded
atom methods which

00:37:16.490 --> 00:37:19.880
we post just for internal
use on the website.

00:37:19.880 --> 00:37:22.820
It's a 1993 Materials Science
and Engineering report.

00:37:22.820 --> 00:37:26.970
It's a really long paper, but
it's really an excellent paper.

00:37:26.970 --> 00:37:29.688
So there are analytical forms.

00:37:29.688 --> 00:37:30.980
And here's a few of them given.

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:32.647
And people have come
up with other ones.

00:37:32.647 --> 00:37:34.430
More and more now,
what people simply do

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:37.160
is tabulate the
embedding function.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:39.560
And really what they
do is they tabulate it

00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:42.840
so that you exactly reproduce
the equation of state.

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:44.090
What is the equation of state?

00:37:44.090 --> 00:37:46.940
The equation of state is
energy versus volume or lattice

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:48.440
parameter.

00:37:48.440 --> 00:37:51.560
So say at every level parameter,
you could try to get that

00:37:51.560 --> 00:37:55.250
energy with a better method--
say, quantum mechanics--

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:57.060
and then fit your
embedding function

00:37:57.060 --> 00:37:59.910
so that you exactly
reproduce that.

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:04.280
And so, often, the embedding
function is tabulated.

00:38:04.280 --> 00:38:10.030
But commonly it has this form.

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:14.630
It's decaying, it's sort
of decreasing convex,

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:17.210
decreasing in energy
and convex, and it

00:38:17.210 --> 00:38:18.950
needs both those properties.

00:38:18.950 --> 00:38:21.920
Well, why does it need to
be decreasing in energy?

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:26.060
So this is the embedding
density and this is the value

00:38:26.060 --> 00:38:27.690
of the embedding function.

00:38:27.690 --> 00:38:30.650
Of course, as you put
more density on a site,

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:31.970
that comes from more neighbors.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:34.863
So your cohesive energy
should be going down.

00:38:34.863 --> 00:38:37.280
That's why the energy of the
embedding function goes down.

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:41.450
But it needs to be convex
because convexity gives you

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:43.400
sort of the correct behavior.

00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:46.700
Convexity really tells you that
adding a bond going from here

00:38:46.700 --> 00:38:47.450
to here--

00:38:47.450 --> 00:38:50.540
let's say a bond is adding 0.01.

00:38:50.540 --> 00:38:56.150
So if we added a bond
here, we'd get this change

00:38:56.150 --> 00:38:58.010
in embedding energy.

00:38:58.010 --> 00:39:03.220
If we added it here, we'd
only get that change.

00:39:03.220 --> 00:39:05.520
So the function has to
be convex in some sense.

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:09.290
Decrease has to be per
unit, and electron density

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:12.260
has to be less for higher
densities than for lower.

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:15.080
And that's the
definition of convex.

00:39:15.080 --> 00:39:19.640
The slope of it has to be
increasing of this function.

00:39:19.640 --> 00:39:23.630
And you see, that's going
to by construction now get

00:39:23.630 --> 00:39:26.300
some of our problems
right because this shape

00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:28.310
of the function,
the convexity is

00:39:28.310 --> 00:39:31.880
what tells you that
the low coordination

00:39:31.880 --> 00:39:34.700
bonds are stronger than the
high coordination bonds.

00:39:37.553 --> 00:39:38.970
So you can already
guess from this

00:39:38.970 --> 00:39:40.887
that we're going to get
a lot of things right.

00:39:48.380 --> 00:39:50.220
I'll show you some
examples in a second.

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:57.438
What's the physical concept
that sort of justifies

00:39:57.438 --> 00:39:58.480
the embedded atom method?

00:40:03.190 --> 00:40:06.700
There are things
you can do formally

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:11.800
in ab initio theory
showing that in fairly

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:13.430
simple tight binding models.

00:40:13.430 --> 00:40:16.630
So these are things
that have the structure

00:40:16.630 --> 00:40:20.560
of a proper quantum
mechanical Hamiltonian,

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:23.590
but they are parameterized
forms of a Hamiltonian.

00:40:23.590 --> 00:40:25.270
But still, what they
all tend to show

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:29.440
is that the cohesive energy
in highly delocalized systems

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:31.390
to first order goals
like the square root

00:40:31.390 --> 00:40:33.470
of the coordination.

00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:35.020
So you can get
some justification

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:37.450
for this nonlinear behavior.

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:41.050
A somewhat intuitive concept of
where the bonding energy comes

00:40:41.050 --> 00:40:46.510
from is that actually,
if you put an atom

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:52.570
in a metallic solid, where does
it get a cohesive energy from?

00:40:52.570 --> 00:40:55.570
For the most part, it
gets its cohesive energy

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:59.410
from the delocalization
of its electrons.

00:40:59.410 --> 00:41:03.292
And that's largely a
kinetic energy effect.

00:41:03.292 --> 00:41:05.500
Remember that the kinetic
energy in quantum mechanics

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:07.930
is the curvature of
the wave function.

00:41:07.930 --> 00:41:15.070
It's d squared phi, dx squared
if you it in one dimension.

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:19.690
So highly curved wave functions
have high kinetic energy.

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:22.420
So if you can
actually delocalize,

00:41:22.420 --> 00:41:24.940
your wave function
becomes, in some sense,

00:41:24.940 --> 00:41:27.190
much smoother with
much less curvature,

00:41:27.190 --> 00:41:30.500
and you have lower
kinetic energy.

00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:34.060
So if you believe that a lot
of bonding cohesive energy

00:41:34.060 --> 00:41:36.280
and delocalized source
comes from that,

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:38.110
then the measure
of cohesive energy

00:41:38.110 --> 00:41:42.520
is essentially how well
you can delocalize it.

00:41:42.520 --> 00:41:47.380
So what do you measure
with the embedding density?

00:41:47.380 --> 00:41:50.380
If you measure the
electron density coming

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:53.170
from atoms, the reason this
works is that that's probably

00:41:53.170 --> 00:41:55.420
a very good measure over
the number of states

00:41:55.420 --> 00:41:57.550
you can delocalize over.

00:41:57.550 --> 00:41:59.063
Things with higher
electron density

00:41:59.063 --> 00:42:00.730
tend to have a higher
number of states--

00:42:00.730 --> 00:42:02.380
higher densities of states.

00:42:02.380 --> 00:42:04.780
And so you can delocalize
over more states.

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:10.210
And that's the somewhat
intuitive explanation

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:12.010
for why the embedded atom works.

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:14.450
I mean, people have given
somewhat other explanations.

00:42:14.450 --> 00:42:18.160
They could say, well,
the electron density

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:20.710
that I see from a
neighboring atom measures

00:42:20.710 --> 00:42:23.600
the number of electrons
I can bond with.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:27.130
But that's not totally true
because if those electrons come

00:42:27.130 --> 00:42:31.810
from a filled shell, there's
nothing I can do with them.

00:42:31.810 --> 00:42:34.120
So somehow, I tend
to believe more

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:36.580
it's really a measure of
the delocalization you see.

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:51.070
The embedded atom
method is-- yes, sir?

00:42:51.070 --> 00:42:53.500
AUDIENCE: Did you
say [INAUDIBLE]??

00:43:00.790 --> 00:43:01.762
PROFESSOR: Correct.

00:43:01.762 --> 00:43:02.637
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:02.637 --> 00:43:03.390
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:43:03.390 --> 00:43:03.890
Yeah.

00:43:03.890 --> 00:43:07.010
So in an atom, you actually have
a much higher kinetic energy

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:09.650
because your state is
much more localized.

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:11.150
The embedded atom
method is probably

00:43:11.150 --> 00:43:14.360
the most popular one of
all these effective medium

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:15.050
theories.

00:43:15.050 --> 00:43:18.020
But you'll see other
ones with other names

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:21.350
that are in spirit very much
the same-- things like the glue

00:43:21.350 --> 00:43:22.640
model.

00:43:22.640 --> 00:43:24.560
Finnis-Sinclair
potentials, which

00:43:24.560 --> 00:43:27.560
slightly predate the
embedded atom method, which

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:30.390
are also non-linear potentials.

00:43:30.390 --> 00:43:33.920
So they're really particle
potential pair functionals.

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:36.230
And the equivalent crystal
models Smith and Banerjee.

00:43:36.230 --> 00:43:40.940
These are all exactly
in the same spirit.

00:43:40.940 --> 00:43:43.820
The brilliance of the
embedded atom method

00:43:43.820 --> 00:43:47.300
was essentially that it
was something for nothing.

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:49.370
The computational
cost is essentially

00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:52.430
the same as for doing pair
potentials because you

00:43:52.430 --> 00:43:54.950
sum things only pairwise.

00:43:54.950 --> 00:43:57.410
If you think of what you
need to do an embedded atom

00:43:57.410 --> 00:44:02.330
calculation, you have
your pair potential.

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:03.950
That's a pairwise sum.

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:07.670
But your embedding energy
is also a pairwise sum.

00:44:07.670 --> 00:44:09.800
Because what you
have to do per atom,

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:11.390
you just have to
sum the electron

00:44:11.390 --> 00:44:16.430
density coming from a bunch
of other atoms around you.

00:44:16.430 --> 00:44:17.773
So that's a pairwise sum.

00:44:17.773 --> 00:44:19.190
And then you just
have to stick it

00:44:19.190 --> 00:44:21.860
in F, which is an
extra evaluation.

00:44:21.860 --> 00:44:27.690
But embedded atom fundamentally
scales only like N squared.

00:44:27.690 --> 00:44:29.660
So that was the
brilliant part of it.

00:44:29.660 --> 00:44:32.270
Or in the end, that's
what made it successful.

00:44:32.270 --> 00:44:36.890
You could essentially
do much better things

00:44:36.890 --> 00:44:39.590
with almost the same
effort as pair potentials.

00:44:39.590 --> 00:44:41.600
And that's why it sort
of took off as a method.

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:43.130
And pretty much
anybody in metals

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:46.310
now would use
embedded atom if they

00:44:46.310 --> 00:44:47.840
want to get any physics right.

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:50.570
If you want to do demonstration
projects or things

00:44:50.570 --> 00:44:52.340
like want to do
billions of atoms,

00:44:52.340 --> 00:44:55.010
there can be reasons to go
through much simpler forces

00:44:55.010 --> 00:44:56.960
still to evaluate.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:59.360
But in metals, there's
really no reason

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:03.368
not to use EM over
simple pair potentials.

00:45:06.950 --> 00:45:08.620
What do people fit to?

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:11.650
People fit to anything,
like I told you before.

00:45:11.650 --> 00:45:14.440
The original EM potentials
were fit to a standard set

00:45:14.440 --> 00:45:17.110
of data, which was lattice
parameter, sublimation

00:45:17.110 --> 00:45:22.180
energy, elastic constants, and
vacancy formation energies.

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:25.870
Now you'll regularly see papers
in the literature claiming,

00:45:25.870 --> 00:45:28.390
I have a better potential
than you for aluminum,

00:45:28.390 --> 00:45:30.670
and I have a better potential
than you for nickel.

00:45:30.670 --> 00:45:32.210
And some of that is true.

00:45:32.210 --> 00:45:34.390
So people are not in the
game of kind of super

00:45:34.390 --> 00:45:37.900
optimizing these potentials
for what it's worth.

00:45:37.900 --> 00:45:40.990
But the original database was
a set of standard potentials--

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:43.510
largely unknowable metal alloys.

00:45:43.510 --> 00:45:47.350
People have spent a lot of
time finding better potentials

00:45:47.350 --> 00:45:50.380
on technologically important
alloys like nickel aluminum.

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:53.320
You'll find at least
five potentials

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:56.500
who all claim to be better
than somebody else's potential

00:45:56.500 --> 00:45:58.090
on the nickel aluminum system.

00:46:02.770 --> 00:46:05.550
So what I want to do now is
just show you some results.

00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:07.900
And we're not going to
analyze these in great deal.

00:46:07.900 --> 00:46:10.440
But I want to show you so
you get some idea of what

00:46:10.440 --> 00:46:12.750
people do with this stuff.

00:46:12.750 --> 00:46:17.700
Here's linear thermal expansion
for a bunch of late transition

00:46:17.700 --> 00:46:22.020
metals calculated in EM and
calculated in experiment.

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:25.690
And these agree pretty well.

00:46:25.690 --> 00:46:30.090
That's maybe not a big surprise
in close packed solids.

00:46:30.090 --> 00:46:32.250
The thermal expansion
is largely a measure

00:46:32.250 --> 00:46:35.650
of the asymmetry of
your equation of state.

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:37.750
I mean, in complex
materials, that's not true.

00:46:37.750 --> 00:46:40.270
But in simple,
close packed metals.

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:43.760
Remember, your equation of
state is slightly asymmetric.

00:46:43.760 --> 00:46:48.630
It curves less towards the
high lattice parameters

00:46:48.630 --> 00:46:49.880
and the low lattice parameter.

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:55.950
So if you draw
energy versus volume,

00:46:55.950 --> 00:46:58.500
it's asymmetric
around the minimum.

00:46:58.500 --> 00:47:00.365
And that's why you
have thermal expansion.

00:47:00.365 --> 00:47:00.990
Think about it.

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:03.780
It's slightly easier to
fluctuate to the higher volume

00:47:03.780 --> 00:47:07.350
than to the lower volume.

00:47:07.350 --> 00:47:08.285
Yes, sir?

00:47:08.285 --> 00:47:12.380
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:12.380 --> 00:47:14.390
PROFESSOR: Oh, good point.

00:47:14.390 --> 00:47:16.370
There is, of course, no
temperature dependence

00:47:16.370 --> 00:47:18.090
in the potential itself.

00:47:18.090 --> 00:47:22.370
So to do something
like thermal expansion,

00:47:22.370 --> 00:47:26.240
you either have to do a dynamic
simulation like molecular

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:29.210
dynamics-- and
we'll come to that--

00:47:29.210 --> 00:47:32.090
or you have to
explicitly calculate

00:47:32.090 --> 00:47:34.970
the entropic factors that give
you thermal expansion, which

00:47:34.970 --> 00:47:37.430
is essentially the
dependence of the phonon

00:47:37.430 --> 00:47:39.290
frequencies on volume.

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:41.540
So you can indirectly calculate
the thermal expansion.

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:44.525
But we sort of
haven't got into-- we

00:47:44.525 --> 00:47:45.770
will go into micro dynamics.

00:47:45.770 --> 00:47:47.437
But of course, in the
potential, there's

00:47:47.437 --> 00:47:49.347
no temperature dependence.

00:47:58.410 --> 00:48:02.260
Here's activation barriers
for self-diffusion in metals.

00:48:02.260 --> 00:48:05.020
These are almost too
good to believe it.

00:48:05.020 --> 00:48:08.570
You actually don't get them this
good with quantum mechanics.

00:48:08.570 --> 00:48:12.580
So it's almost surprising to
me that they're this good,

00:48:12.580 --> 00:48:14.080
if you compare EM to external.

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:18.980
So this is the
activation barrier for--

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:19.720
I forget.

00:48:19.720 --> 00:48:22.020
But I thought it was
interstitials self-diffusion,

00:48:22.020 --> 00:48:25.180
but I'm not for sure whether
it was interstitial or vacancy

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:26.395
self-diffusion.

00:48:30.360 --> 00:48:34.350
You know, here's a bunch
of surface energies.

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:38.580
These are not quite as
good as the experiment.

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:44.020
If you, for example,
look at copper,

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:50.480
here's the experimental number
in ergs per centimeter squared.

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:54.220
And here is the calculation
on different facets.

00:48:54.220 --> 00:48:56.680
Because of course,
often experimentally

00:48:56.680 --> 00:48:59.560
you measure some average
of different facets.

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:01.810
Unless you do careful
single crystal work,

00:49:01.810 --> 00:49:04.653
you have some average.

00:49:04.653 --> 00:49:06.820
On the calculations you
have to calculate the energy

00:49:06.820 --> 00:49:07.900
on a specific surface.

00:49:07.900 --> 00:49:09.520
And that's actually
one of the things

00:49:09.520 --> 00:49:11.630
you're going to do in the lab.

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:14.590
So these are a little lower.

00:49:14.590 --> 00:49:17.350
And that seems to be a rather
consistent problem that is,

00:49:17.350 --> 00:49:20.670
for example, also in platinum.

00:49:20.670 --> 00:49:25.290
These are quite a bit
lower than the experiment.

00:49:25.290 --> 00:49:28.950
So that may tell you
that either there

00:49:28.950 --> 00:49:32.310
are more complicated quantum
mechanical effects going on

00:49:32.310 --> 00:49:36.360
that you don't capture with
these simple energy models.

00:49:36.360 --> 00:49:39.360
But sometimes, it also means
the experiment is wrong.

00:49:39.360 --> 00:49:42.840
I think in this case, platinum
is a fairly easy metal

00:49:42.840 --> 00:49:45.090
to deal with clean.

00:49:45.090 --> 00:49:46.980
But surface energies
of materials

00:49:46.980 --> 00:49:50.750
is sort of notoriously
difficult to get experimental.

