00:49:56.910 --> 00:49:58.620
Again, don't worry
about the details.

00:49:58.620 --> 00:50:01.280
I just wanted to show you
the kind of things people do.

00:50:01.280 --> 00:50:05.510
Calculations are the
lines and the points

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:07.280
are the measurements.

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:10.310
So, reasonably good
at some of these.

00:50:10.310 --> 00:50:12.890
High frequencies there seems
to be some problems with.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:18.610
Melting point.

00:50:18.610 --> 00:50:21.070
Again, this would have been
done with molecular dynamics

00:50:21.070 --> 00:50:23.050
and then free
energy integration.

00:50:23.050 --> 00:50:27.840
And again, for most materials,
these come out remarkably well.

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:29.620
So, look at this.

00:50:29.620 --> 00:50:32.945
Except again for the very
late transition metals

00:50:32.945 --> 00:50:34.570
like palladium and
platinum, there just

00:50:34.570 --> 00:50:37.240
seems to be some
amount of problems.

00:50:37.240 --> 00:50:40.840
I can tell you in a second
about the limitations

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:41.800
of these methods.

00:50:41.800 --> 00:50:48.080
And they may be related to the
unusual electronic structure

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:49.450
of palladium and platinum.

00:50:52.210 --> 00:50:54.280
You know, here's a pair
correlation function

00:50:54.280 --> 00:50:56.290
in a liquid.

00:50:56.290 --> 00:50:58.150
[? People, ?]
[? we're ?] [? good? ?]

00:50:58.150 --> 00:51:01.090
A grain boundary.

00:51:01.090 --> 00:51:02.890
This is something
you simply could not

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:05.590
do with a pair
potential in metals

00:51:05.590 --> 00:51:08.020
because when you calculate
a grain boundary,

00:51:08.020 --> 00:51:12.790
you really are dealing
with different coordinated

00:51:12.790 --> 00:51:14.020
environments.

00:51:14.020 --> 00:51:16.120
And the painful thing
about a grain boundary

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:20.477
is that you don't know ahead of
time what kind of coordinations

00:51:20.477 --> 00:51:21.310
you're going to see.

00:51:21.310 --> 00:51:24.258
And you're going to see
multiple coordinations.

00:51:24.258 --> 00:51:26.050
See, but people with
potentials always get,

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:29.070
if I know I'm going to
deal with a surface,

00:51:29.070 --> 00:51:31.290
I can make a pair
potential that's

00:51:31.290 --> 00:51:34.650
pretty good for those
coordinations at the surface.

00:51:34.650 --> 00:51:36.960
If I deal with the bulk,
I make a pair potential

00:51:36.960 --> 00:51:39.373
that's pretty good with
bulk coordinations.

00:51:39.373 --> 00:51:41.040
It's when you work
with grain boundaries

00:51:41.040 --> 00:51:43.980
that you kind of end up with
all kinds of coordinations

00:51:43.980 --> 00:51:45.930
because the atoms in
the grain boundary,

00:51:45.930 --> 00:51:48.930
some are high coordinated,
some are low coordinated,

00:51:48.930 --> 00:51:51.630
depending on how the
grains contact each other.

00:51:55.660 --> 00:52:00.070
So it's a great method, but
it still has its limitations.

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:04.440
One is that the
bonding is spherical.

00:52:04.440 --> 00:52:07.950
You literally sum all
the electron density

00:52:07.950 --> 00:52:12.670
coming from around you, and
you really just sum it up.

00:52:12.670 --> 00:52:14.820
You don't keep track of
its orientation dependence.

00:52:14.820 --> 00:52:19.140
So having one atom there next
to me and one atom on that side

00:52:19.140 --> 00:52:22.693
is the same as having both
straight in front of me

00:52:22.693 --> 00:52:24.735
because I just sum up the
electron density coming

00:52:24.735 --> 00:52:27.810
from them So it's
purely spherical.

00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:30.330
That can be fixed.

00:52:30.330 --> 00:52:34.380
About in the '90s, [? Mike ?]
[? Baskis ?] developed

00:52:34.380 --> 00:52:38.460
what's called a MEAM, and
that just stands for modified

00:52:38.460 --> 00:52:42.660
embedded atom method, which
basically has embedding

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:47.160
functions that keep track
of the angular dependence

00:52:47.160 --> 00:52:49.110
of the electron
density around you,

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:51.600
essentially by mapping the
problem on to spherical

00:52:51.600 --> 00:52:53.100
harmonics.

00:52:53.100 --> 00:52:57.360
MEAM is not nearly as
popular as the standard EM

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:02.310
because it adds a level of
complexity to the method.

00:53:02.310 --> 00:53:05.790
And it's not totally
clear that you're

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:09.360
making things work because
the physics is better

00:53:09.360 --> 00:53:11.922
or you just have more
fitting parameters.

00:53:11.922 --> 00:53:14.130
[? Mike ?] [? Baskis ?]
originally developed the MEAM

00:53:14.130 --> 00:53:17.850
to work on silicon where
angular dependence clearly seems

00:53:17.850 --> 00:53:19.450
to play an important role.

00:53:19.450 --> 00:53:21.950
Yes, sir?

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:25.304
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:37.652 --> 00:53:38.860
PROFESSOR: Well, your force--

00:53:38.860 --> 00:53:39.220
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:39.887
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:53:39.887 --> 00:53:41.860
Your force is
directional dependent

00:53:41.860 --> 00:53:45.490
because you're taking
the derivative of energy

00:53:45.490 --> 00:53:49.330
with respect to a vector,
which is some distance.

00:53:49.330 --> 00:53:50.277
But--

00:53:50.277 --> 00:53:53.546
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:00.130 --> 00:54:03.130
PROFESSOR: But again, the force
will be directional dependent.

00:54:03.130 --> 00:54:04.520
Let me show you an example.

00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:07.720
Let's say I have a
central atom here

00:54:07.720 --> 00:54:11.950
and I got four atoms around it.

00:54:11.950 --> 00:54:16.080
The force will be directional
dependent because--

00:54:16.080 --> 00:54:17.380
what is the force?

00:54:17.380 --> 00:54:20.050
The force is how the
energy of an atom

00:54:20.050 --> 00:54:23.535
changes as I move it into
a particular direction.

00:54:23.535 --> 00:54:24.910
So the force along
this direction

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:27.730
is the energy change as I move
the atom along this direction

00:54:27.730 --> 00:54:30.880
because it is the derivative of
the total energy with respect

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:35.000
to some unit vector
in that direction.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:36.652
See, if I change
in this direction,

00:54:36.652 --> 00:54:38.110
I'm going to
significantly increase

00:54:38.110 --> 00:54:40.480
the overlap with that atom.

00:54:40.480 --> 00:54:44.980
But if I change it,
say, in this direction,

00:54:44.980 --> 00:54:49.030
that's not necessarily
the same derivative

00:54:49.030 --> 00:54:51.360
than in this direction.

00:54:51.360 --> 00:54:55.080
So the force will be directional
dependent just because

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:58.530
of the crystallography,
but the energy is not.

00:54:58.530 --> 00:55:01.530
So what I mean
with that is that--

00:55:01.530 --> 00:55:08.570
let's call this some unit
length L, and they're all at L.

00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:15.750
If I do this, and
here's my central atom,

00:55:15.750 --> 00:55:22.400
and these are all L, that gives
me exactly the same embedding

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:24.585
energy as in the first problem.

00:55:24.585 --> 00:55:26.460
Of course, the total
energy will be different

00:55:26.460 --> 00:55:29.480
because these guys
interact very closely.

00:55:29.480 --> 00:55:31.370
But the bonding energy
of the central atom

00:55:31.370 --> 00:55:32.570
is exactly the same.

00:55:32.570 --> 00:55:34.850
And that's what I mean
with no angular dependence.

00:55:37.590 --> 00:55:41.130
It doesn't in the end see
what orbitals that electron

00:55:41.130 --> 00:55:44.450
density comes from.

00:55:44.450 --> 00:55:46.700
And when you think about
angular dependence,

00:55:46.700 --> 00:55:50.630
in the end, what it is, it
is polarization of orbitals.

00:55:50.630 --> 00:55:52.980
Think of sp3 bonding.

00:55:52.980 --> 00:55:54.940
What is that really telling you?

00:55:54.940 --> 00:55:58.010
If I do an sp3 hybrid
along this direction,

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:00.290
I'm really starting to
polarize the orbitals along--

00:56:00.290 --> 00:56:00.790
what is it--

00:56:00.790 --> 00:56:03.300
109 degrees in other directions.

00:56:03.300 --> 00:56:08.190
So I really need to try to get
my bonds in those directions.

00:56:08.190 --> 00:56:11.090
So that's essentially what
angular dependence comes from.

00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:14.425
Does that help?

00:56:14.425 --> 00:56:16.050
AUDIENCE: [? I ?]
[? think ?] [? so. ?]

00:56:16.050 --> 00:56:16.768
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:56:16.768 --> 00:56:17.310
You think so.

00:56:17.310 --> 00:56:20.540
Well, let me know if it doesn't.

00:56:20.540 --> 00:56:22.970
OK.

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:24.710
The other problem
is-- which is more

00:56:24.710 --> 00:56:27.542
a technical problem-- is that
the potential is not unique.

00:56:27.542 --> 00:56:29.000
And this is something
you just have

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:30.770
to be careful with
if you start messing

00:56:30.770 --> 00:56:33.410
around with potential
files yourself.

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:38.420
If you're going to use it as a
black box, you're probably OK.

00:56:38.420 --> 00:56:40.100
Let me get you
some notes on that.

00:56:48.982 --> 00:56:51.190
The way you can see that
the potential is not unique.

00:56:54.230 --> 00:56:58.400
If I have an embedding
function F of rho,

00:56:58.400 --> 00:57:01.100
if I define another
embedding function-- we

00:57:01.100 --> 00:57:04.160
call it G of rho-- they're
always the electron density.

00:57:04.160 --> 00:57:09.650
And I say, that's F of rho
plus some linear term in rho.

00:57:12.380 --> 00:57:17.230
You could make the total energy
function exactly the same

00:57:17.230 --> 00:57:18.980
with either of the two
embedding functions

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:20.660
just by changing
the pair potential.

00:57:20.660 --> 00:57:22.100
And let me show you that.

00:57:22.100 --> 00:57:30.260
If I write the energy
as the sum over atoms,

00:57:30.260 --> 00:57:36.600
the embedding function on
that atom, plus some air

00:57:36.600 --> 00:57:37.500
potential part.

00:57:48.130 --> 00:57:51.920
Let me substitute this in.

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:56.050
So I get that this is sum i.

00:57:56.050 --> 00:58:13.850
Fi rho plus 1/2 sum
iJ psi iJ, RiJ, plus--

00:58:13.850 --> 00:58:26.310
let me-- sum i k sum J
[? not equal ?] i of f

00:58:26.310 --> 00:58:36.090
rj where rho i was sum j f.

00:58:36.090 --> 00:58:37.390
OK.

00:58:37.390 --> 00:58:41.310
Essentially, if you want
to look through the math,

00:58:41.310 --> 00:58:43.380
don't worry too much about it.

00:58:43.380 --> 00:58:46.320
If you do a linear
transformation on the embedding

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:52.380
function, you see this term
is linear in things coming

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:54.960
from the atoms around it.

00:58:54.960 --> 00:58:58.990
It's linear in these
electron density functions.

00:58:58.990 --> 00:59:02.220
So anything that's
linear in functions

00:59:02.220 --> 00:59:05.593
that I sum from the other atoms
is just like a pair potential

00:59:05.593 --> 00:59:07.260
because that's what
a pair potential is.

00:59:07.260 --> 00:59:09.900
I sum contributions, OK?

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:12.720
I add up contributions
from the things around me.

00:59:12.720 --> 00:59:15.580
So I'm linear in
that contribution.

00:59:15.580 --> 00:59:19.200
So any linear part of
the embedding function

00:59:19.200 --> 00:59:20.600
just looks like a potential.

00:59:20.600 --> 00:59:21.870
This is a pair potential.

00:59:21.870 --> 00:59:24.300
This is the sum over
[? 2n. ?] This is i an J,

00:59:24.300 --> 00:59:25.950
and I add something up.

00:59:25.950 --> 00:59:30.600
So this I could
just add the psi.

00:59:30.600 --> 00:59:34.320
So if I add psi to this and
use the embedding function F,

00:59:34.320 --> 00:59:37.440
I have exactly the same as
using the embedding function G

00:59:37.440 --> 00:59:39.600
and using just
the potential psi.

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:43.320
So the linear part you
can move arbitrarily

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:48.150
between the embedding function
and the pair potential.

00:59:48.150 --> 00:59:53.170
So that tells you something
else that's kind of important.

00:59:53.170 --> 00:59:57.160
When is a pair potential
alone good in metals?

01:00:02.520 --> 01:00:05.610
It's when the embedding
part doesn't change.

01:00:05.610 --> 01:00:09.970
If my atoms stay roughly
at the same density,

01:00:09.970 --> 01:00:13.900
then all the changes come
from the pair potential part.

01:00:13.900 --> 01:00:15.010
OK?

01:00:15.010 --> 01:00:19.090
So what would you do--

01:00:19.090 --> 01:00:42.560
[INAUDIBLE]---- if you're
having an embedding function

01:00:42.560 --> 01:00:44.970
as a function of rho.

01:00:44.970 --> 01:00:49.940
If you're working,
say, at this density?

01:00:49.940 --> 01:00:51.690
Let's sort of say the
density of the bulk,

01:00:51.690 --> 01:00:53.790
and you're studying
bulk problems.

01:00:53.790 --> 01:00:58.600
You could take the slope of
this, take the linear term,

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:01.170
make a linear
approximation to that

01:01:01.170 --> 01:01:02.910
and add that to
the pair potential,

01:01:02.910 --> 01:01:05.160
and now you wouldn't have
to worry about the embedding

01:01:05.160 --> 01:01:06.900
function.

01:01:06.900 --> 01:01:09.720
So at constant density,
pair potentials

01:01:09.720 --> 01:01:11.860
are actually pretty good.

01:01:11.860 --> 01:01:13.380
It's when the
density around you--

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:15.013
the electron density
around you changes

01:01:15.013 --> 01:01:17.430
which is, in essence, a measure
of the coordination change

01:01:17.430 --> 01:01:19.770
that you run into trouble.

01:01:19.770 --> 01:01:22.470
And so, people have gone
into that game of making

01:01:22.470 --> 01:01:26.138
density dependent potentials.

01:01:26.138 --> 01:01:27.930
And so you would have
a different potential

01:01:27.930 --> 01:01:30.480
when you're near a surface
than when you're near the bulk.

01:01:40.460 --> 01:01:42.945
So my summary on
effective medium theories

01:01:42.945 --> 01:01:44.570
which I showed by
embedded atom methods

01:01:44.570 --> 01:01:47.198
is, in essence, that there's
no reason not to use them.

01:01:47.198 --> 01:01:48.740
If you've decided
you're going to use

01:01:48.740 --> 01:01:53.990
an empirical model for metals,
there's really no reason at all

01:01:53.990 --> 01:01:56.420
to use pair potentials.

01:01:56.420 --> 01:02:01.393
Embedded atom basically does
better at very little cost.

01:02:01.393 --> 01:02:02.810
Saying that it
does better doesn't

01:02:02.810 --> 01:02:06.180
say that the does everything.

01:02:06.180 --> 01:02:08.810
And I remember talking to people
like [? Mike ?] [? Baskis ?]

01:02:08.810 --> 01:02:09.860
who invented this.

01:02:09.860 --> 01:02:13.530
They're embarrassed for
kind of things people now do

01:02:13.530 --> 01:02:14.780
with the embedded atom method.

01:02:14.780 --> 01:02:17.900
Like with any successful method,
people push it way too hard

01:02:17.900 --> 01:02:21.080
and try to calculate all
kinds of subtle energy effects

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:23.840
that it just never was made for.

01:02:23.840 --> 01:02:25.460
And you see people
write papers on,

01:02:25.460 --> 01:02:29.810
if I change my
constant by 1,000 here,

01:02:29.810 --> 01:02:31.760
I can get this phase correct.

01:02:31.760 --> 01:02:35.150
But in the end, it gives
you these gross coordination

01:02:35.150 --> 01:02:38.900
effects right, but it does
not give you very subtle

01:02:38.900 --> 01:02:41.570
hybridization effects right.

01:02:41.570 --> 01:02:46.550
Why, for example, were platinum
and palladium not so good?

01:02:46.550 --> 01:02:50.800
Because platinum and palladium
have almost filled or filled

01:02:50.800 --> 01:02:53.180
D bands.

01:02:53.180 --> 01:02:56.150
And as a function of the
environment around platinum

01:02:56.150 --> 01:02:59.240
and palladium, there is very
subtle electron transfer

01:02:59.240 --> 01:03:01.710
between the D band
and the S band.

01:03:01.710 --> 01:03:02.380
OK?

01:03:02.380 --> 01:03:04.380
And when you're just
measuring electron density,

01:03:04.380 --> 01:03:06.200
that all looks the
same, but those states

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:08.750
behave very differently.

01:03:08.750 --> 01:03:11.420
So there will be always
subtle electronic change

01:03:11.420 --> 01:03:12.650
that you simply won't get.

01:03:12.650 --> 01:03:17.770
And if your system is really
influenced strongly by those,

01:03:17.770 --> 01:03:19.300
you won't get them right.

01:03:19.300 --> 01:03:23.480
For example, people try to
get complex crystal structure

01:03:23.480 --> 01:03:27.320
differences in metals with EM.

01:03:27.320 --> 01:03:29.230
You will just never
get there, period.

01:03:31.770 --> 01:03:33.500
Let's say you make an alloy--

01:03:33.500 --> 01:03:38.990
palladium ruthenium, whatever--
the crystal structure energy

01:03:38.990 --> 01:03:41.000
difference in that
[? material, ?] like in most

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:45.260
metals over the order of 5 to
10 millielectron [? volt. ?] You

01:03:45.260 --> 01:03:48.500
cannot get things right on that
scale with these kind of simple

01:03:48.500 --> 01:03:50.340
models, so you
shouldn't try too hard.

01:03:50.340 --> 01:03:52.340
But on the other hand,
if you're going to study,

01:03:52.340 --> 01:03:58.010
say, I don't know, fracture in
a material in a simple element

01:03:58.010 --> 01:04:01.160
like one of these big
movies I showed you,

01:04:01.160 --> 01:04:03.830
that's to a large extent
a topological event.

01:04:06.790 --> 01:04:10.515
You will get a lot of
essential pieces of that right.

01:04:10.515 --> 01:04:11.390
Because what is that?

01:04:11.390 --> 01:04:13.760
That's a coordination
change event, largely.

01:04:13.760 --> 01:04:17.278
You will get a lot of that right
by doing EM over potentials.

01:04:23.270 --> 01:04:25.250
This is a great
website I only added

01:04:25.250 --> 01:04:27.380
that this year to
the lecture I found.

01:04:27.380 --> 01:04:29.330
There's a group in
Japan that called

01:04:29.330 --> 01:04:34.820
themselves the [? EAMers. ?]
They even have a blog now.

01:04:34.820 --> 01:04:37.570
And so there's a lot of
cool stuff you can download.

01:04:37.570 --> 01:04:39.890
They have potential files.

01:04:39.890 --> 01:04:44.120
You can get EM code
from the Sandia site.

01:04:44.120 --> 01:04:46.050
It's a little hard to
get to, because Sandia

01:04:46.050 --> 01:04:50.240
being a national
lab, they're totally

01:04:50.240 --> 01:04:53.630
paranoid about
downloading anything.

01:04:53.630 --> 01:04:56.480
But there are sources where
you can get the EM code.

01:04:56.480 --> 01:04:59.360
It is technically
freely available.

01:04:59.360 --> 01:05:02.120
It's just not necessarily
trivial to get to it.

01:05:06.920 --> 01:05:12.120
So we talked about
pair functionals,

01:05:12.120 --> 01:05:13.870
which was this direction.

01:05:13.870 --> 01:05:15.390
So the other
direction is obviously

01:05:15.390 --> 01:05:18.240
to go to cluster potentials.

01:05:18.240 --> 01:05:20.880
Well, you know, I
don't like my expansion

01:05:20.880 --> 01:05:22.740
in just two-body terms.

01:05:22.740 --> 01:05:25.430
I'll start adding
three-body terms.

01:05:25.430 --> 01:05:26.920
It's the obvious extension.

01:05:26.920 --> 01:05:29.730
And if you don't like that,
you can go to four-body terms.

01:05:35.450 --> 01:05:37.280
That's definitely done.

01:05:37.280 --> 01:05:42.110
And for reasons I'll go into
in the next lecture on Tuesday,

01:05:42.110 --> 01:05:43.730
it's extremely
popular in the world

01:05:43.730 --> 01:05:46.610
of organics, where it's actually
really, really powerful.

01:05:46.610 --> 01:05:49.940
And we'll go into
why that is the case.

01:05:49.940 --> 01:05:51.740
But a typical material
in condensed matter

01:05:51.740 --> 01:05:54.500
where obviously this
was done was silicon.

01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:57.320
Silicon is a low coordinated
solid-- only fourfold

01:05:57.320 --> 01:05:59.390
coordinated in the
diamond cubic structure.

01:05:59.390 --> 01:06:01.830
It's extremely hard to get
that with a pair potential

01:06:01.830 --> 01:06:06.860
because again, your systems
always try to form FCC or HGP,

01:06:06.860 --> 01:06:09.000
essentially.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:13.550
So what you can do is build
a three-body potential

01:06:13.550 --> 01:06:18.240
that favors these 190-degree
tetrahedral angles.

01:06:18.240 --> 01:06:20.480
And as soon as you do
that, if you actually

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:22.520
make that force
strong enough, you

01:06:22.520 --> 01:06:25.813
can do almost nothing else
than form diamond cubic.

01:06:25.813 --> 01:06:27.230
Because diamond
cubic is basically

01:06:27.230 --> 01:06:31.745
the way to pack atoms and put
them under all these 109--

01:06:31.745 --> 01:06:36.210
what is it-- .4 or
something degree angles.

01:06:36.210 --> 01:06:38.780
So if you make a strong
enough three-body force,

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:45.740
you will by definition end up
in the diamond cubic structure.

01:06:45.740 --> 01:06:49.190
If you work with
three coordinates,

01:06:49.190 --> 01:06:51.290
you can also transform
that and instead

01:06:51.290 --> 01:06:54.500
work with two
distances and an angle.

01:06:54.500 --> 01:06:57.600
So if I have three atoms,
the coordinates of them,

01:06:57.600 --> 01:07:00.800
I can also always say that to
have the relation between them,

01:07:00.800 --> 01:07:03.890
I just need to have these two
distances and this angle that

01:07:03.890 --> 01:07:06.560
fully defines the
three-body problem.

01:07:06.560 --> 01:07:08.600
And that's usually
how it's done.

01:07:08.600 --> 01:07:12.020
People have pair potentials
that take care of the distance

01:07:12.020 --> 01:07:13.500
dependence of that.

01:07:13.500 --> 01:07:15.740
And then they have
an angular potential

01:07:15.740 --> 01:07:17.960
which takes care of the
angle between these.

01:07:17.960 --> 01:07:20.300
And often, the prefactor
of the angular potential

01:07:20.300 --> 01:07:22.610
will have some
distance depends in it.

01:07:22.610 --> 01:07:24.380
Because of course,
maybe you want

01:07:24.380 --> 01:07:26.810
to enforce this
190-degree angle when

01:07:26.810 --> 01:07:28.700
your two other atoms are close.

01:07:28.700 --> 01:07:32.300
But when they're very far,
you don't really care anymore.

01:07:32.300 --> 01:07:35.720
What's the possible choices
for angular potentials?

01:07:35.720 --> 01:07:40.700
The simplest one is simply a
quadratic-- a harmonic function

01:07:40.700 --> 01:07:42.650
in the angle.

01:07:42.650 --> 01:07:45.710
If you want to impose
an angle theta naught,

01:07:45.710 --> 01:07:50.970
you make a potential
that's literally

01:07:50.970 --> 01:07:54.140
a quadratic around theta naught.

01:07:54.140 --> 01:07:57.450
So, extremely
simple to evaluate.

01:07:57.450 --> 01:08:00.150
So that function's
actually often used.

01:08:00.150 --> 01:08:01.940
You can also use--

01:08:01.940 --> 01:08:06.120
the disadvantage of this one
is that it's not periodic.

01:08:06.120 --> 01:08:08.145
Angle measurements
should be periodic.

01:08:08.145 --> 01:08:10.020
So you can kind of get
into trouble with this

01:08:10.020 --> 01:08:11.980
if you go too far
from equilibrium.

01:08:11.980 --> 01:08:14.940
So another thing you can use
is a cosine function which

01:08:14.940 --> 01:08:16.950
has the proper periodicity.

01:08:16.950 --> 01:08:18.540
If you take--

01:08:18.540 --> 01:08:19.560
I don't know--

01:08:19.560 --> 01:08:22.890
109 degrees or whatever
angle you want, or you

01:08:22.890 --> 01:08:24.470
take its complement--

01:08:24.470 --> 01:08:28.359
360 minus that-- you
should get the same answer.

01:08:28.359 --> 01:08:31.380
And so, cosine functions
will do that right.

01:08:31.380 --> 01:08:34.890
And this one, cosine
theta plus 1/3, this part

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:41.628
is minimal when theta is
109 with tetrahedral angle.

01:08:41.628 --> 01:08:43.439
[CLEARS THROAT] Excuse me.

01:08:43.439 --> 01:08:44.760
Losing my voice.

01:08:44.760 --> 01:08:47.370
So it works working with
three-body potentials.

01:08:47.370 --> 01:08:49.300
It's, of course, more work.

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:51.930
It's not [? order ?] N cubed.

01:08:51.930 --> 01:08:54.810
Because, for every
atom, you now have

01:08:54.810 --> 01:08:58.500
to look at distance and
angles with pairs of atoms.

01:08:58.500 --> 01:09:02.370
OK so it becomes an N cubed
operation, so it's more work.

01:09:02.370 --> 01:09:05.760
And calculating the forces as
the derivatives of the energy

01:09:05.760 --> 01:09:07.450
is also quite a bit more work.

01:09:17.710 --> 01:09:20.800
The most famous three-body
potential is probably

01:09:20.800 --> 01:09:24.609
the Stillinger Webber potential
which, as you can see,

01:09:24.609 --> 01:09:27.189
has this cosine
theta form for the--

01:09:27.189 --> 01:09:30.130
this is the angular part.

01:09:30.130 --> 01:09:34.029
This is the distance
dependence of the angular part.

01:09:34.029 --> 01:09:38.529
So how much should you penalize
angular deviations [INAUDIBLE]..

01:09:38.529 --> 01:09:40.500
And then this is
the two-body part.

01:09:40.500 --> 01:09:44.500
Just sort of a more
[? slight ?] potential.

01:09:44.500 --> 01:09:48.042
Originally, Stillinger
Webber, when they actually

01:09:48.042 --> 01:09:49.750
wrote down the function,
they didn't even

01:09:49.750 --> 01:09:52.069
fit it very carefully.

01:09:52.069 --> 01:09:55.150
I mean, it was a great form,
but they just kind of did

01:09:55.150 --> 01:09:56.260
a rough fit.

01:09:56.260 --> 01:09:58.510
And so, the original
Stillinger Webber parameters

01:09:58.510 --> 01:10:00.738
and the ones people now
use sometimes more recently

01:10:00.738 --> 01:10:01.780
are not the same anymore.

01:10:01.780 --> 01:10:03.190
The potential has the same form.

01:10:03.190 --> 01:10:05.650
But some people have done
recently better fits.

01:10:05.650 --> 01:10:09.220
So when somebody says that
Stillinger Webber potential,

01:10:09.220 --> 01:10:11.740
there are variations of
it for the constants.

01:10:19.700 --> 01:10:23.110
So what do you get
right with a [? sale ?]

01:10:23.110 --> 01:10:27.190
something like a Stillinger
Webber potential?

01:10:27.190 --> 01:10:30.070
Well, you can kind of
guess why people did this.

01:10:30.070 --> 01:10:31.620
Because silicon is
so important, they

01:10:31.620 --> 01:10:33.120
wanted to be able to
model silicon right.

01:10:33.120 --> 01:10:35.770
So it's important to understand
which pieces you get right.

01:10:38.770 --> 01:10:42.910
One of the critical issues
was surface reconstruction.

01:10:42.910 --> 01:10:44.836
If you take silicon 111--

01:10:44.836 --> 01:10:47.650
sorry, 100.

01:10:47.650 --> 01:10:51.400
If you truncate it,
it actually undergoes

01:10:51.400 --> 01:10:53.530
a 2 times 1 reconstruction.

01:10:53.530 --> 01:11:00.170
What essentially happens if
you take this top layer atoms,

01:11:00.170 --> 01:11:03.550
they're only bonded to
two atoms below them,

01:11:03.550 --> 01:11:06.070
and so they dimerize
on the surface.

01:11:06.070 --> 01:11:08.860
So basically,
these move together

01:11:08.860 --> 01:11:11.570
in sort of double rows.

01:11:11.570 --> 01:11:13.590
I need a better color.

01:11:13.590 --> 01:11:16.560
And then these
will move together.

01:11:16.560 --> 01:11:19.950
And so they double the
periodicity in one direction.

01:11:19.950 --> 01:11:22.040
And so you have these
dimers that form.

01:11:22.040 --> 01:11:24.080
And because of that,
the surface atom

01:11:24.080 --> 01:11:26.510
is bonded to three other atoms--

01:11:26.510 --> 01:11:29.622
two below it, one all
the way in the surface.

01:11:29.622 --> 01:11:30.830
And so they're better bonded.

01:11:30.830 --> 01:11:33.290
And that's the 2 by
1 reconstruction.

01:11:33.290 --> 01:11:36.290
The 2 by 1 reconstruction you
get right with the Stillinger

01:11:36.290 --> 01:11:37.370
Webber potential.

01:11:37.370 --> 01:11:39.860
You'd actually get it
right with almost anything.

01:11:39.860 --> 01:11:43.370
It's essentially a
topological reconstruction.

01:11:43.370 --> 01:11:47.030
You know, atoms like to have
more atoms around them to bond,

01:11:47.030 --> 01:11:48.110
period.

01:11:48.110 --> 01:11:51.560
And so that's what drives
a 2 by 1 reconstruction.

01:11:51.560 --> 01:11:55.970
At the top layer, atoms now are
at least threefold coordinated

01:11:55.970 --> 01:11:59.960
and they're actually almost
fourfold coordinated instead

01:11:59.960 --> 01:12:04.350
of twofold coordinated at just
an unreconstructed terminated

01:12:04.350 --> 01:12:04.850
surface.

